Anonymous Fri 12 Jan 2024 02:49:09 No.62515809 Report
Quoted By:
>>62514681
Understand what you want to write about and the kind of stories you want to tell.

Understand your characters. You as the writer should at least know their core traits and beliefs, their relationships with each other, and the arcs they go through over the course of the plot.

Allow your characters to evolve naturally as you write. I don’t just mean inside the story, I mean in your head too. As you spend more time with the character they start developing and growing more and more, almost like you’re getting to know a soon-to-be good friend. Eventually you can introduce a random event in your head and your character should respond immediately without you having to think about it.

Spend maybe around 100 words a day just writing about something. Can be anything. Like eating a chocolate bar. The shards as it crumbles to your teeth, the burning sweetness as it slides down your throat, the flash of foil in the sun.

Sometimes, less is more. Read Hemingway and Salinger’s short stories for masterclasses in elliptical writings.

Purple prose is incredibly hard to pull off and will make any amateurish writer look foolish. Better not to attempt it when beginning. If you do want to try a crack at it, read Nabokov and Fitzgerald to understand what you’re going up against.

Keep writing. Fail quickly and stupidly.

Most importantly, have fun! Writing that comes from a place of passion always has a special quality to it.

No water supply a "star" for with 13th century exterior walls (which were circular with bastions), way too much interior greener, but at least has a multi-layered keep.

None of these have proper gate houses but thats the least concern.

Yeah that's true
There still Isekais nowadays that I personally believe so fun stuff with it
For example one of the big tropes that you see in modern Isekai stories is after the main character Gets a power that is either way too powerful and makes the entire conflict almost not there, or somehow way too convenient and is used to give him basically modern life like making fridges and shit
But there are some fun ones with nice changes
For example, how about the hero who gets isekai'd is already powerful when he comes to the other world? He doesn't uses the world magic or stuff like that, the dude was already with superpowers before he came to the world, like the one manga where iori yagami from the KOF series goes into a fantasy world, or the one where the dude who Gets transported is like a bootleg red power ranger (love that one because I like power ranger/Kamen rider shit and it also has a fluffy girl)
There are other examples too like have the main character who makes modern tech instead of making things to make his life comfortable, he makes weapons of war like rifles and TNT (Survival in Another World with My Mistress)
Or just straight up have the character not be with an OP ability but that would be hard because these are sadly always written as power fantasies
